Answer:
&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you can see here: &lt;a href="http://php.net/manual/en/pdostatement.fetchcolumn.php" rel="nofollow"&gt;http://php.net/manual/en/pdostatement.fetchcolumn.php&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;There is no way to return another column from the same row if you use
  PDOStatement::fetchColumn() to retrieve data.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is because each time you call fetchColumn it will apply over the row next to the row on which the previous call applied. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt; $salt = $stmt-&amp;gt;fetchColumn(0);
$activation = $stmt-&amp;gt;fetchColumn(1);
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The second call to fetchColumn() is working over the row next to that of the first call. In your case, as there is only one row, fetchColumn() returns NULL, so that's why activation appears as empty.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Use fetch() to retrieve an array with all the values of the row:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;   $row=$stmt-&amp;gt;fetch();
   $salt=$row[0];
   $activation=$row[1];
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

